<paragraph blockId="10.[264,1323,284,470]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Remarks. The brown vestiture of the body, brown patterns of the legs, wing venation, and the three white tomentose stripes on the pleuron of 
<taxonomicName box="[909,1020,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hypnus">
<emphasis box="[909,1020,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. hypnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1187,1323,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apoticius">
<emphasis box="[1187,1323,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. apoticius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[314,440,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="misamis">
<emphasis box="[314,440,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. misamis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in the brown fore coxa and trochanters, and in the characters of the male terminalia (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Oldroyd" box="[570,740,404,430]" pageId="10" pageNumber="22" refString="Oldroyd, H. (1972) Robber flies (Diptera: Asilidae) of the Philippine Islands. Pacific Insects, 14, 201 - 337." type="journal article" year="1972">
Oldroyd 
<number box="[679,740,404,430]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, Figure 
<number box="[845,892,404,430]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="125.0">125</number>
), especially the wide, emarginated, yellow apex of the median branch of the epandrium.
</paragraph>
